    {
      "id": "pipelines",
      "type": "code",
      "accent": "green",
      "kicker": "04 // COMPOSITION",
      "heading": "Everything is an Op",
      "file": "crates/rig-core/src/pipeline/op.rs",
      "lang": "rust",
      "code": "// The pipeline is a DAG of operations. Each one implements:\npub trait Op: Send + Sync {\n    type Input:  Send + Sync;\n    type Output: Send + Sync;\n\n    /// The one method every op must implement.\n    fn call(&self, input: Self::Input)\n        -> impl Future<Output = Self::Output> + Send;\n}\n\n// Combinators chain ops — map, then, chain — alongside AI ops\n// like `prompt` and `lookup`. No orchestration runtime required:\nlet pipeline = pipeline::new()\n    .map(|(x, y)| x + y)\n    .map(|z| format!(\"result: {z}\"));\n\nlet result = pipeline.call((2, 3)).await;   // \"result: 5\"",
      "beats": [
        {
          "id": "pipelines-1",
          "narration": "Rig's pipeline API is inspired by orchestration frameworks like Airflow and Dagster -- but built from idiomatic Rust traits, with no runtime underneath.",
          "note": "crates/rig-core/src/pipeline"
        },
        {
          "id": "pipelines-2",
          "narration": "Everything is an Op. A trait with two associated types -- an input and an output -- and exactly one required method: call.",
          "highlight": [
            2,
            9
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "pipelines-3",
          "narration": "Because call is the only requirement, a plain closure is an Op. So is an L-L-M prompt. So is a vector-store lookup. They all compose the same way.",
          "highlight": [
            6,
            8
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "pipelines-4",
          "narration": "Combinators chain them. This pipeline adds two numbers, then formats the result -- a directed graph of operations, type-checked end to end, with no scheduler beneath it.",
          "highlight": [
            12,
            16
          ]
        }
      ]
